          "body": "Verses 13–18 and 26–27 form the chapter's household cluster. The sage examines the family from multiple angles: the foolish son is destruction to his father, and a quarrelsome wife is like a constant dripping (v. 13) — two forms of relentless, wearing erosion of the household's peace. But verse 14 pivots sharply: house and wealth are what fathers pass down, but a prudent wife is the LORD's gift. The contrast is significant — material inheritance is humanly transferable; the right spouse is divinely bestowed. Then verse 18 delivers the chapter's most urgent household command: discipline your son while hope remains, or you participate in his death. The word *tiqvah* (hope) names a closing window — the time for formative correction is now, before the character solidifies into the fool of verse 29. Verse 26 closes the household section with the negative image: the son who assaults his father and drives out his mother is shameful and disgraceful (*bush, chapher*). The household is the primary workshop of character formation in Proverbs; Proverbs 19 takes that workshop with full seriousness."
