          "body": "Verse 21 is the chapter's theological statement about history and human agency: *many plans are in a man's heart, but the counsel of the LORD will stand*. The Hebrew *etsah* appears in both halves — human counsel (v. 20, accept it) and divine counsel (v. 21, it prevails). The sage does not dismiss human planning; he relativizes it. The same word used for the wise man's counsel that should be accepted (v. 20) reappears as the LORD's counsel that will stand regardless (v. 21). This is not fatalism but wisdom — the recognition that human designs, however numerous and energetic, operate within a sovereign framework they do not control. Proverbs 16:9 offers the parallel: *the mind of man plans his way, but the LORD directs his steps*. The pastoral implication is not passivity but humility — plan carefully, accept counsel, and hold your plans loosely before the God whose purpose alone endures."
