          "body": "Verse 17 is one of the most theologically arresting statements in Proverbs: *one who is gracious to a poor man lends to the LORD, and He will repay him for his good deed*. The verb *lavah* (to lend) is the language of commercial transaction — the sage deliberately uses economic vocabulary to reframe charity. The person who shows *chanan* (gracious favor) to the poor is not losing capital; he is making a loan to YHWH Himself, who will repay. Jesus' parable of the sheep and the goats (Matthew 25:31–46) echoes this identification: what is done to the least is done to the Lord. Proverbs 19:17 is not merely a motivational incentive for generosity; it is a theological statement about God's identification with the poor. Combined with the chapter's framing of poverty (vv. 1, 22) and the abandonment of the poor by friends (vv. 4, 7), verse 17 offers the decisive counter-word: the God whom human society ignores when it ignores the poor is the same God who will repay."
