        "body": "Proverbs 19's household cluster (vv. 13–18, 26–27) addresses the family as the primary institution of character formation. The chapter examines the household from both directions — what damages it (v. 13: the foolish son and the contentious wife) and what the LORD supplies to it (v. 14: the prudent wife). The contrast in verse 14 is theologically precise: house and wealth are transferable human goods, inherited through normal channels. A prudent (*sakhal*, wise, discerning) wife is categorically different — she is from the LORD. This does not mean human effort is irrelevant; it means that some goods exceed what human acquisition can produce.\n\nVerse 18 is the chapter's most urgent pastoral command directed at parents: *discipline your son while there is hope*. The word *tiqvah* (hope) carries the weight of an open window — the sage pictures a window of formative opportunity that is real now but will close. The second half of the verse is difficult; the NASB 1995 reads *do not desire his death*, which is almost certainly a warning against the passivity that amounts to passive complicity in the son's destruction. Failing to discipline when the window is open is, in the sage's logic, preferring the son's death to the discomfort of correction. D. A. Carson's observation about parenting and the tension between affection and discipline is directly applicable: excessive permissiveness is not kindness; it is abdication.\n\nVerse 26 closes with the terminal portrait of the undisciplined son: he assaults his father and drives his mother out. The verbs *shadad* (to violently despoil) and *barach* (to cause to flee) are words for predatory aggression, not adolescent rebellion. The son who was not formed in verse 18 becomes the aggressor of verse 26. The trajectory is deliberate: the chapter frames parental discipline not as optional enrichment but as life-or-death formation.\n\nVerse 27 addresses the son himself: *cease listening to discipline, my son, and you will stray from the words of knowledge*. The direct address (*my son*) invokes the classic wisdom-teacher voice of Proverbs 1–9. The warning is not that straying causes one to stop learning; it is that the cessation of listening to discipline is itself already straying. Withdrawal from formation is not a neutral act; it is the beginning of the ruin described in verse 3.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Musar* (discipline, vv. 18, 20, 27) — from *yasar*, to chasten, correct, instruct. Not mere punishment but the whole formative process. *Tiqvah* (hope, v. 18) — from *qavah*, to wait expectantly. The hope is real but timed. *Sakhal* (prudent, v. 14) — to act wisely, to have good insight; the feminine participle applied to the wife the LORD gives."
